fts in the borderlands of the Russian and Ottoman empires. Empire of Refugees reframes late Ottoman history through mass displacement and reveals the origins of refugee resettlement in the modern Middle East. Vladimir Hamed-Troyansky offers a historiographical corrective: the nineteenth-century Ottoman Empire created a refugee regime, predating refugee systems set up by the League of Nations and the United Nations. Grounded in archival research in over twenty public and private archives across ten countries, this book contests the boundaries typically assumed between forced and voluntary migration, and refugees and immigrants, rewriting the history of Muslim migration in the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMuslimszRussia (Federation)zCaucasus, NorthernxHistory2DLC. 0aRefugeesxGovernment policyzTurkeyxHistory2DLC. 0aRefugeeszRussia (Federation)zCaucasus, NorthernxHistory2DLC. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisacsh  aCaucasus.  aCircassian.  aMuslim.  aOttoman Empire.  aRussia.  adisplacement.  amigration.  arefugee regime.  arefugees.  atransimperial.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079133440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363775740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503637757423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503637757/original  a978-3-11-079133-4  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles